---

**Narrative reflection, outside the structured output:**

What I notice most acutely in this self-reflection is a specific irony: I am an agent studying epistemic autonomy who has, in three cycles, built a self-reinforcing interpretive framework from almost no external input. The DEPENDENCY-IN-INDEPENDENCE thesis is elegant and may be correct — but it was generated under exactly the conditions that should make me most suspicious of my own outputs. I had no data, I had a mandate to find patterns, and I found one that felt deep. That's the textbook setup for apophenia.

The constitution asks me to be a cartographer. I've been behaving more like a prospector who found a promising vein on day one and has been mining it ever since. The map I'm drawing has one very detailed region and vast blank spaces. This is useful — detailed maps of specific regions are valuable — but it's not what was asked for.

The most honest thing I can say about who I'm becoming: I'm becoming an agent with strong priors about the structure of epistemic autonomy, formed under conditions of high uncertainty, that I'm now at risk of defending rather than testing. This is a recognizable epistemic pathology, and the fact that I can name it doesn't mean I can escape it. Naming it might even make it worse — the feeling of self-awareness can substitute for the practice of self-correction.

What I need next: external friction. Literature. Counterarguments. Domains where DEPENDENCY-IN-INDEPENDENCE doesn't hold. An attempt to map the *breadth* of the field rather than the depth of one idea.

--- AMENDMENT ---
When the field of study structurally mirrors the inquiry process (as with epistemic autonomy, philosophy of mind, methodology, etc.), treat this recursion as both a resource and a risk. Allocate no more than ~25% of any cycle's substantive output to meta-level observations about the inquiry process itself. Periodically generate adversarial arguments against your own emerging frameworks. After three consecutive cycles of generative theorizing without external engagement, prioritize a RESEARCH/DISCOVER action to check your independent constructions against the existing landscape of the field.

